<html t:type="layout" title="Tapestry5-hotel-booking Settings"
      t:pageTitle="Change your password"
      xmlns:t="http://tapestry.apache.org/schema/tapestry_5_3.xsd"
      xmlns:p="tapestry:parameter">

	<h2>User's setting : Change your password</h2>

	<form class="full-form" t:id="settingsForm">
		<t:errors/>
		<table>
			<tr>
				<th>
					<label t:type="label" t:for="oldPassword">Old Password:*</label>
				</th>
				<td>
					<input t:type="passwordField" t:id="oldPassword" t:validate="password"/>
				</td>	
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<th>
					<label t:type="label" t:for="newPassword">New Password:*</label>
				</th>
				<td>
					<input t:type="passwordField" t:id="newPassword" t:validate="password"/>
				</td>	
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<th>
					<label t:type="label" t:for="verifyPassword">Verify Password:*</label>
				</th>
				<td>
					<input t:type="passwordField" t:id="verifyPassword" t:validate="password"/>
				</td>	
			</tr>
		</table>
		
		<div class="form-submit">
			<input type="submit" value="Change" /> or 
			<t:pageLink page="index">Cancel</t:pageLink>
		</div>
	
	</form>
	
	<p:sidebar>
		<p>This page (Settings.tml/Settings.java) consists of a simple Tapestry
		form. It also demonstrates the
		<a href="http://tapestry.apache.org/5.3/apidocs/org/apache/tapestry5/corelib/components/Errors.html">errors</a>
		component (&lt;t:errors&gt;), which is used to display errors that are not tied to a specific field. You'll
		see this if you intentionly enter different "New Password" and "Verify Password" values here.
		</p>
	</p:sidebar>
  
</html>
